{
  "text": "In this paper, we develop an AFPTAS for GCBP. We develop a framework, where the action of the scheme for a given non-decreasing concave function f with f (0) = 0 is based on its exact definition. We also develop a new approximation algorithm MATCHHALF (MH), which acts obliviously of f , similarly to the behavior of the algorithms of [CITATION_1] . We prove that our algorithm has an asymptotic approximation ratio of at most 1.5 for any non-decreasing concave function f with f (0) = 0, improving over the tight bound of approximately 1.691, proved by Anily et al. [CITATION_2] , on the asymptotic approximation ratio of NFI. The classic bin packing problem is clearly a special case of GCBP as one can set f (0) = 0 and f (i) = 1 for all i ≥ 1, where the resulting function is monotonically non-decreasing and concave. Therefore, GCBP inherits the hardness proof of the classic bin packing problem. That is, GCBP cannot be approximated within an absolute factor better than 3 2 (unless P = N P ). This motivates our use of asymptotic approximation ratio as the main analytic tool to study approximation algorithms for GCBP. In this metric we design the best possible result (assuming P = N P ), i.e., an AFPTAS.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "8937327",
